buffer_a_code:
/*

    Offset Grid Prism Traversal
    ---------------------------

    I wanted to produce a grid traverser that most wouldn't have seen, so 
    here's a grid of towering offset rectangular prisms. So far, all cell
    by cell traversal tilings on Shadertoy have consisted of edge-to-edge 
    arrangements; The defalt scene here is not. Additionally, I wanted to 
    construct something that could only be raytraced via a cell by cell 
    traversal approach. That is to say, a scene with so much overlap that 
    you couldn't raymarch it on a repeat grid... I wouldn't say raymarching 
    this would be impossible, but I haven't seen it done yet.

    I've had a glitchy version of this sitting around for a while, but wasn't 
    motivated to fix it and finish it until recently. I'm not a fan of 
    writing traversal code, but like a lot of people, I can write a regular 
    square grid pylon or voxel traverser without too much trouble -- Mostly
    becaues that was a pretty common coding task back in the 90s, or the 
    olden days, as some of the younger crowd would say. :)

    Because I was lazy and didn't want to start from scratch, I used IQ's
    "Grid of Cylinders" as a template. There's not much of the original left
    at this point, but that shader and a few of IQ's other ones were an 
    invaluable reference, which I've listed below. I also referenced a couple
    of Fizzer's examples.

    It would have been nice to render a few samples, but I'd imagine slow 
    machines would have a hard enough time rendering this in one sample mode, 
    so I left it alone. However, I did the next best thing and utilized IQ's 
    temporal camera reprojection routine to give the impression that a few 
    samples were taken. I've said this before, but I feel IQ's reprojection
    code is one of the coolest underutilized pieces of code on here.

    There's a bit of code here, but not too much. For whatever reason, I got
    bored and included options to raymarch hexagons and a non offset rectangle
    option. That complicated things a bit, but if you were to traverse just a
    single grid, the code size and entanglement would drop considerably.

    I plan to put up some more interesting traversals later. By the way, if
    you're interested in less common 3D traversals, Fizzer's work is definitely 
    worth looking at.


    References:

    // Raymarching inside of traversed cells. Very cool, and I intend to
    // make use of it at some stage. In fact, I used it as a template for 
    // the example you're looking at, then proceeded to overwrite almost 
    // all of it. However, I did keep a couple of cool lighting snippets 
    // and variable names. :)
    Grid of Cylinders - iq
    https://www.shadertoy.com/view/4dSGW1

    // IQ's 3D hexagonal traverser: It's beautifully rendered and the 
    // traversal code leaves very little room for improvement.
    Hexagonal Grid Traversal - 3D -- iq
    https://www.shadertoy.com/view/WtSfWK

    // I like the traversal code on this. When producing a single traverser of
    // a tiled plane with joining neighboring vertex points, this is the method
    // I'll be using.
    Triangle Grid Traversal - fizzer
    https://www.shadertoy.com/view/WtBfDd

    // A rough 2D version of this that is much easier to consume. If 
    // you can understand the following, then this will make more sense.
    Offset Grid Traversal - Shane
    https://www.shadertoy.com/view/fdScWd



*/

// Maximum distance.
#define FAR 1e8

// Make use of IQ's well written temporal reprojection code. Unfortunately, 
// if you have a slow machine, all you'll see is blur, so you'll need
// to turn it off.
#define REPROJECTION


// Hexagon option. 
//#define HEXAGON

// Offset grid rows.
#define OFFSET

// Hexgons must have an offset defined.
#ifdef HEXAGON
#ifndef OFFSET
#define OFFSET
#endif
#endif

#define sqrt3 1.7320508 // sqrt(3.).

// Scale.
#ifdef HEXAGON
// Hexagons will only work with the "1 to sqrt3" ratio -- Scaling is fine though. 
// At some stage, I'll arrange for anything to work, but it's not trivial.
const vec2 s = vec2(1, sqrt3)*1.5; 
#else
// Rectangle dimensions. Any numbers should work. Obviously, vec2(1)
// will produce squares.
const vec2 s = vec2(1.5, 1); 
#endif

// Standard 2D rotation formula.
mat2 rot2(in float a){ float c = cos(a), s = sin(a); return mat2(c, -s, s, c); }

// IQ's vec2 to float hash function.
float hash21(vec2 p) { return fract(sin(dot(p, vec2(1 , 113)))*43758.5453123); }


// The path is a 2D sinusoid that varies over time, which depends upon the 
// frequencies and amplitudes.
vec2 path(in float z){ 
    //return vec2(0);
    return vec2((cos(z*.36/8.)*1. - sin(z*.2/8.)*1.2)*6., sin(z*.12/2.)*3.);
} 


// The height function.
float map(vec2 p){ 

    // Only one texture read.
    vec3 tx = texture(iChannel0, p/iChannelResolution[0].xy).xyz;  tx *= tx;
    // Greyscale height. Using "tx.x" would work, too.
	float f = dot(tx, vec3(.299, .587, .114));
    float f2 = min(f, .44); // Ground noise, so it doesn't look too flat.

    // Using the camera path to carve out a channel for the camera to glide through.
    vec2 pth = path(p.y);
    float pX = abs(p.x - pth.x); // The channel.
    f *= clamp(pX*pX/24., 0., 1.); // Carving it out.

    // Returning the terrain and ground noise, then adding the undulating camera
    // height to keep the ground close to the viewer for that rollercoaster feel. :)
	return f*40. + f2*14. + pth.y;
}

// Sign function without the zero, which can cause problems for some routines.
vec3 sign2(in vec3 p){ return vec3(p.x<0.? -1 : 1, p.y<0.? -1 : 1,  p.z<0.? -1 : 1); }
//vec2 sign2(in vec2 p){ return vec2(p.x<0.? -1 : 1, p.y<0.? -1 : 1); }


// Grid cell function.
vec2 gridID(vec2 p){


    // Returns the cell center position-based IDs for a hexagon 
    // grid, offset rectangle grid and regular rectangle grid.

    #ifdef HEXAGON

    // Hexagons.  
    //
    vec4 hC = floor(vec4(p/s, p/s - vec2(.5, sqrt3/3.))) + .5;
    vec4 h = vec4(p - hC.xy*s, p - (hC.zw + .5)*s);
    return dot(h.xy, h.xy)<dot(h.zw, h.zw) ? hC.xy : hC.zw + .5;

    #else

    // Rectangles.   
    //    
    #ifdef OFFSET
    // Rectangles with an offset. 
    vec2 idOff = vec2(0);
    if(mod(floor(p.y/s.y), 2.)>.5){
       p.x -= s.x/2.;
       idOff.x += .5;
    }
    vec2 ip = floor(p/s) + .5;
    //p -= (ip)*s;
    return ip + idOff;
    #else
    // Rectangles with no offset. 
    vec2 ip = floor(p/s) + .5;
    //p -= (ip)*s;
    return ip;
    #endif    

    #endif

}


/*
// Ray origin, ray direction, point on the line, normal. 
float rayLine(vec2 ro, vec2 rd, vec2 p, vec2 n){

    // Normally, there'd be more checks, but the boundary lines 
    // have been chosen such that a hit will always occur.    
    float s = dot(p - ro, n)/dot(rd, n);
    return s<0. ? 1e8 : s;
}
*/

// Ray origin, point on the line, normal. 
float rayLineF(vec2 ro, vec2 p, vec2 n){

    // Normally, there'd be more checks, but the boundary lines 
    // have been chosen such that a hit will always occur.    
    return dot(p - ro, n);

}


// Cell by cell prism traversal: It is literally the same as 2D traversal,
// but you're testing for a top plane hit as well. That's explained below.
// There are three sets of tile traversals here. All are regular and monohedral,
// and two are edge-to-edge. The offset retangles are not edge-to-edge, so need 
// to be handled differently.
vec4 raycast( in vec3 ro, in vec3 rd ){

    // Result, unit vector directions, and initial postion.
    vec4 res = vec4(1e8); // Distance, face ID and cell ID.
    vec3 srd = sign2(rd); 
    vec3 pos3 = ro; 



    #ifdef HEXAGON
    // Hexagon edge normals -- Only three faces and the top can be hit by the ray.
    // Any three normals will do.
    vec3 i1 = vec3(.5, 0, .5); // Right forward face index.
    vec3 i2 = vec3(1, 0, 0); // Right face index.
    vec3 i3 = vec3(-.5, 0, .5); // Left forward face index.
    vec3 n1 = vec3(.5, 0, sqrt3/2.); // Right forward.
    vec3 n2 = vec3(1, 0, 0); // Right face normal.
    vec3 n3 = vec3(-.5, 0, sqrt3/2.); // Left forward.
    //vec3 nT = vec3(0, 1, 0); // Top face.

    // Back face selection: When the ray swings in the direction of the 
    // back face, use the opposing index and normal. You can only use this
    // trick when there's... opposing face symmetry involved. Although, with 
    // an assymetric polygon, you'll still want to check this to avoid doing
    // the ray face distance calculation.
    float d1 = dot(rd.xz, n1.xz);
    float d2 = dot(rd.xz, n2.xz);
    float d3 = dot(rd.xz, n3.xz); 
    // As discussed above.
    if(d1<0.) { i1 *= -1.; n1 *= -1.; }
    if(d2<0.) { i2 *= -1.; n2 *= -1.; }
    if(d3<0.) { i3 *= -1.; n3 *= -1.; }

    vec3 invN = -1./vec3(dot(rd, n1), dot(rd, n2), dot(rd, n3));

    // Minimum distance from the current cell position to the opposing
    // planes, which covers the planes in front of the ray in the
    // direction it's travelling.
    vec3 t;

    #else
    // Square edge normals -- Only two faces and the top can be hit by the ray.
    // Any two normals will do. Indexes and normals are the same, in this case.
    vec3 n1 = vec3(1, 0, 0); // Right face normal.
    vec3 n2 = vec3(0, 0, 1); // Forward (or back) face normal.
    //vec3 nT = vec3(0, 1, 0); // Top face.

    float d1 = dot(rd.xz, n1.xz);
    float d2 = dot(rd.xz, n2.xz); 

    if(d1<0.) n1 *= -1.;
    if(d2<0.) n2 *= -1.;

    vec2 invN = -1./vec2(dot(rd, n1), dot(rd, n2));

    // Minimum distance from the current cell position to the opposing
    // planes, which covers the planes in front of the ray in the
    // direction it's travelling.
    vec2 t;

    #endif




    // Minimum top plane distance.
    float tT;

    // Minimum plane difference, and total distance.
    float mint = 0.;// dist = 0.;

    // Plane hit. The default is no hit.
    int hit = 0;

    vec2 ip = gridID(pos3.xz);

    for(int i = 0; i<160; i++){


        res.zw = ip*s;
        float ma = map(res.zw); 


        // At this point, we haven't advanced the ray to the back of the cell boundary,
        // so we're at one of the front cell face positions. Therefore, check to see if 
        // we're under the pylon height. If so, we've hit a face, so mark the face as hit, 
        // then break.
        if(pos3.y<ma){
            // Hit a side.
            hit = 1;
            break; 

        } 

        #ifdef HEXAGON        
        // Hexagon.
        // Ray origin, ray direction, point on the line, normal.
        // Side face distances.
        t.x = rayLineF(pos3.xz, res.zw + i1.xz*s*.5, -n1.xz);
        t.y = rayLineF(pos3.xz, res.zw + i2.xz*s*.5, -n2.xz);
        t.z = rayLineF(pos3.xz, res.zw + i3.xz*s*.5, -n3.xz);

        t *= invN;

        mint = min(min(t.x, t.y), t.z);   

        // Normal selection, but not needed here.
        //vec3 n = t.x>t.y && t.x<t.z? n1 : t.y<t.z? n2 : n3;

        #else

        // Square.
        // Ray origin, ray direction, point on the line, normal. 
        // Side face distances.
        t.x = rayLineF(pos3.xz, res.zw + n1.xz*s*.5, -n1.xz);
        t.y = rayLineF(pos3.xz, res.zw + n2.xz*s*.5, -n2.xz);

        t *= invN;

        mint = min(t.x, t.y);

        // Normal selection, but not needed here.
        //vec3 n = t.x<t.y? n1 : n2;

        #endif

        // Top face distance.
        tT = (ma - pos3.y)/(rd.y);
        tT = tT<0. ? 1e8 : tT;


        // We've now advanced to one of the back faces of the cell. Check to see whether
        // we're still under the pylon height, and if so, we've hit the top face --  
        // I always have to think about this, but the logic is that we haven't hit a front
        // cell face and we're still under the height, so we've hit the top. Anyway, mark 
        // the top face as hit, advance the distance in the Y direction to the top face, 
        // then break.
        if(tT<mint){

            //dist += tT;
            pos3 += rd*tT; 
            hit = 2;
            break;

        }      


         // Top plane, early exit.
         //if(pos3.y>60.) { dist = 1e8; break; }


         // Adding the minimum distance.
         //dist += mint;
         // Updating the position.
         pos3 += rd*mint; 

         // For hexagon and non offset rectangles, and other tilings where all vertices
         // are shared by neighbors, you should call this once (outside the loop), then 
         // add the index relating to the shortest side. However, for offset rectangles, 
         // this isn't the case, so we call it every iteration. Having said that, it's 
         // not a hugely expensive operation and there's no face normal selection, so
         // all in all, this isn't too bad at all.
         ip = gridID(pos3.xz + srd.xz*.001);

    } 


    if(hit>0){

        // Flag a top hit for use in normal calculations.
        // The prism sides are calculated via polar angles.
        res.y = hit == 2? 0. : 1.; 
        /*
        // Face ID, to determine normals.
        #ifdef HEXAGON        
        res.y = t.x<t.y && t.x<t.z && t.x<tT? 1. : t.y<t.z && t.y<tT? 2. : t.z<tT? 3. : 0.;
        if(res.y == 1. && d1<0.) res.y *= -1.;
        if(res.y == 2. && d2<0.) res.y *= -1.;
        if(res.y == 3. && d3<0.) res.y *= -1.;
        #else
        res.y = t.x<t.y && t.x<tT? 1. : t.y<tT? 2. : 0.;      
        if(res.y == 1. && d1<0.) res.y *= -1.;
        if(res.y == 2. && d2<0.) res.y *= -1.;
        #endif
        */

        res.x = length(pos3 -  ro);

    }
    else {

        // If we don't record a hit, max out the distance.
        res.x = 1e8;
        //res.y = -1e8;
    }

    // Return the distance, the faceID and the cell ID.
    return res; // length(ro - pos3) 

}    





// Cell by cell prism traversal for shadows:
float castShadowRay(in vec3 ro, in vec3 rd){

    // Unit ray direction vector and initial position.
    vec3 srd = sign2(rd);
    vec3 pos3 = ro;


    #ifdef HEXAGON
    // Hexagon edge normals -- Only three faces and the top can be hit by the ray.
    // Any three normals will do.
    vec3 i1 = vec3(.5, 0, .5); // Right forward face index.
    vec3 i2 = vec3(1, 0, 0); // Right face index.
    vec3 i3 = vec3(-.5, 0, .5); // Left forward face index.
    vec3 n1 = vec3(.5, 0, sqrt3/2.); // Right forward.
    vec3 n2 = vec3(1, 0, 0); // Right face normal.
    vec3 n3 = vec3(-.5, 0, sqrt3/2.); // Left forward.
    //vec3 nT = vec3(0, 1, 0); // Top face.

    float d1 = dot(rd.xz, n1.xz);
    float d2 = dot(rd.xz, n2.xz);
    float d3 = dot(rd.xz, n3.xz); 

    if(d1<0.) { i1 *= -1.; n1 *= -1.; }
    if(d2<0.) { i2 *= -1.; n2 *= -1.; }
    if(d3<0.) { i3 *= -1.; n3 *= -1.; }

    vec3 invN = -1./vec3(dot(rd, n1), dot(rd, n2), dot(rd, n3));

    // Minimum distance from the current cell position to the opposing
    // planes, which covers the planes in front of the ray in the
    // direction it's travelling.
    vec3 t;

    #else
    // Square edge normals -- Only two faces and the top can be hit by the ray.
    // Any two normals will do. Indexes and normals are the same, in this case.
    vec3 n1 = vec3(1, 0, 0); // Right face normal.
    vec3 n2 = vec3(0, 0, 1); // Forward (or back) face normal.
    //vec3 nT = vec3(0, 1, 0); // Top face.

    float d1 = dot(rd.xz, n1.xz);
    float d2 = dot(rd.xz, n2.xz); 

    if(d1<0.) n1 *= -1.;
    if(d2<0.) n2 *= -1.;

    vec2 invN = -1./vec2(dot(rd, n1), dot(rd, n2));

    // Minimum distance from the current cell position to the opposing
    // planes, which covers the planes in front of the ray in the
    // direction it's travelling.
    vec2 t;

    #endif


    float mint = 0.; 

    // Result: Shadowed or not.
    float res = 1.;

    vec2 ip = gridID(pos3.xz);


    for(int i = 0; i<64; i++){

        vec2 id = ip*s; 

        float ma = map(id);  

        if(pos3.y<ma){
            // Hit a side.
            res = 0.;
            break; 

        }

        #ifdef HEXAGON        
        // Hexagon.
        // Ray origin, ray direction, point on the line, normal. 
        t.x = rayLineF(pos3.xz, id + i1.xz*s*.5, -n1.xz);
        t.y = rayLineF(pos3.xz, id + i2.xz*s*.5, -n2.xz);
        t.z = rayLineF(pos3.xz, id + i3.xz*s*.5, -n3.xz);

        t *= invN;

        mint = min(min(t.x, t.y), t.z); 

        #else

        // Square.
        // Ray origin, ray direction, point on the line, normal. 
        t.x = rayLineF(pos3.xz, id + n1.xz*s*.5, -n1.xz);
        t.y = rayLineF(pos3.xz, id + n2.xz*s*.5, -n2.xz);

        t *= invN;

        mint = min(t.x, t.y);

        #endif

        // Top plane distance.
        float tT = (ma - pos3.y)/(rd.y);
        tT = tT<0. ? 1e8 : tT; 

        // Top plane hit.
        if(tT<mint){

            // Hit the top.
            res = 0.;
            break;
        }  

        // Top plane, early exit.
        //if(pos3.y>60.){ dist = 1e8; break; }


        pos3 += rd*mint; 

        ip = gridID(pos3.xz + srd.xz*.001);

    }    

    return res;
}    


// mat3 rotation... I did this in a hurry, but I think it's right. :)
// I have a much better one than this somewhere. 
mat3 rot(vec3 ang){

    vec3 c = cos(ang), s = sin(ang);

    return mat3(c.x*c.z - s.x*s.y*s.z, -s.x*c.y, -c.x*s.z - s.x*s.y*c.z,
                c.x*s.y*s.z + s.x*c.z, c.x*c.y, c.x*s.y*c.z - s.x*s.z,
                c.y*s.z, -s.y, c.y*c.z);    
}


void mainImage( out vec4 fragColor, in vec2 fragCoord ){


    #ifdef REPROJECTION
    // Initial hit point and distance.
    vec3 resPos = vec3(0);
    float resT = 1e8;
    #endif

    // Screen coordinates: The coordinates are already in one to one ratio form, so 
    // a simple translation and scaling is all that is necessary in this setting.
    vec2 uv = (fragCoord - iResolution.xy*.5)/iResolution.y;

    // Experiment involving random jittering: Visually speaking, it's better in some 
    // ways and worse in others. There are always trade offs with cheaper effects.
    //vec2 tm = fract(iTime*vec2(.01327, .02183));
    //uv += (vec2(hash21(uv + tm.x), hash21(uv + tm.y)) - .5)/2./iResolution.y;


    // Lens warping -- Needs to be performed camera side to work with
    // temporal reprojection, but I've forgotten how... I'll look at one
    // of Dr2's examples at some stage to see how it's done.
    //uv *= 1. + dot(uv, uv)*.2;


    // Ray origin.
    vec3 ro = vec3(0, 7, iTime*8.);


    // "Look At" position.
    vec3 lk = ro + vec3(0, -.0, 1.);//vec3(0, -.25, iTime);  


	// Sending the camera and "look at" vectors along the path. The "path" function is 
	// synchronized with the distance function.
    ro.xy += path(ro.z);
	lk.xy += path(lk.z);


    // Using the above to produce the unit ray-direction vector.
    float FOV = .75; // FOV - Field of view.

    vec3 fwd = normalize(lk - ro);    
    vec3 rgt = normalize(vec3(fwd.z, 0., -fwd.x)); 
    // "right" and "forward" are perpendicular, due to the dot product being zero. Therefore, I'm 
    // assuming no normalization is necessary? The only reason I ask is that lots of people do 
    // normalize, so perhaps I'm overlooking something?
    vec3 up = cross(fwd, rgt); 

    // Camera.
    mat3 mCam = mat3(rgt, up, fwd);

    // Camera movement. Rotation, swivle, etc.
    mCam *= rot(vec3(-path(ro.z).x/32., 0, 0)); // Camera roll.
    //mCam *= rot(vec3(0, 0, iTime/4.)); // Camera pitch.

    // Unit direction ray.
    vec3 rd = mCam*normalize(vec3(uv, 1./FOV));

    // Directional light.
    vec3 ld = normalize(vec3(.2, .7, .8)); 


    // Sky function, based on one of IQ's simple snippets. 	
    float sun = clamp(dot(rd, ld), 0., 1.);
    vec3 sky = mix(vec3(1, .75, .6), vec3(1, .75, .6).xzy, max(rd.y, 0.)*.5);
    sky += .3*pow(sun, 4.);

    // Scene function, initially set to the sky.
    vec3 col = sky;

    // Raycasting.
    vec4 res = raycast( ro, rd );
    vec2 cellID = res.zw;
    float ry = res.y;
    float t = res.x;

    // If we've hit the scene geometry, render it.
    if(t<1e8 - 1e-4){


        // 3D surface postion.
        vec3 pos = ro + rd*t;
        float rnd = hash21(cellID + .04);

        // Local 2D cell face coordinates -- Centered at vec2(0).
        vec2 lP = pos.xz - cellID;

        // Cell height.
        float h = map(cellID);

        #ifdef REPROJECTION
        // Only save the initial hit point and 
        // distance. Ignore other bounces.
        resPos = pos;
        resT = t;
        #endif




        #ifdef HEXAGON
        const float aNum = 6.;
        #else
        const float aNum = 4.;
        #endif


        // Normal and texture UV coordinates. You should do this via face
        // identification in your raycasting function, but I was curious
        // to see if could be done this way. You can, but I wouldn't advise
        // it. I'll update this with something easier to read later.
        //
        // Top facing.
        vec3 nor = vec3(0, 1, 0);
        vec2 tuv = pos.xz - hash21(cellID + .2 + h)*8.;// - vos;

        if(abs(res.y)>.01){

           vec2 qq = lP; // Centered 2D cell face coordinates.

           #ifdef HEXAGON
           qq *= rot2(-3.14159/aNum); 
           // Prism side angle matrix, relative to the center.
           float aa = (floor(atan(qq.y, qq.x)/6.2831*aNum) + .5)/aNum;
           mat2 mR = rot2(-aa*6.2831);
           // Right plane, then rotate.
           nor.xz = mR*vec2(1, 0);
           nor.y = 0.;

            // UV coordinates.
           // The X coordinate is the local XZ coordinates dotted with the 
           // face normal. There are other ways to do this, but that's the 
           // easist way. The Y coordinate is just the Y position.
           tuv = vec2(dot((lP), nor.xz), pos.y);
           // Adjusting the UV by the height and a random figure for some 
           // cell face texture variance. 
           tuv -= vec2(hash21(cellID + aa + .1), h);


           // Rotating the normal back to the center.
           nor.xz *= rot2(3.14159/aNum);
           #else

           float aa;
           if(dot(qq, s.yx)<0.) {
               if(dot(qq, s.yx*vec2(1, -1))<0.){ nor = vec3(-1, 0, 0); aa = 0.; tuv.x = qq.y; }
               else{ nor = vec3(0, 0, -1); aa = 1.; tuv.x = qq.x; }
           }
           else {
               if(dot(qq, s.yx*vec2(1, -1))>0.){  nor = vec3(1, 0, 0); aa = 2.; tuv.x = qq.y; }
               else{ nor = vec3(0, 0, 1); aa = 3.; tuv.x = qq.x; }
           }

           tuv.y = pos.y;

           //tuv = vec2(dot((pos.xz - vos), nor.xz*rot2(3.14159/aNum)), pos.y);
           tuv -= vec2(hash21(cellID + aa + .1), h);
           #endif


        }




        // Object color.	
        vec3 objCol = .5 + .45*sin(rnd*6.2831/6. + vec3(0, 1, 2)/3. + 2.);

        // Applying some texture.
        vec3 tx = texture(iChannel1, rot2(-3.14159/6.)*tuv/4. + h).xyz; tx *= tx;
        vec3 tx2 = texture(iChannel1, rot2(3.14159/3.)*tuv/2. + .33).xyz; tx2 *= tx2;
        tx = mix(tx, tx2, .5);
        objCol *= .35 + tx*1.5;


        // Very rough ambient occlusion. It's designed to give the feel of AO,
        // but it won't be winning any awards, that's for sure. :)
        float occ = 1.;//   + nor.y*.5; // Occlusion.
        float ds = 1.; // Analogous to sample spread. // .01*t           
        float k = .3;//.05/ds;  // Intensity.
        float dst = ds*1.; // Initial distance.          

        for(int i = 0; i<4; i++){
            //vec2 oCoord = pos.xz + nor.xz*dst;
            //vec2 ps = mix(oCoord, gridID(oCoord)*s, .5);
             float hn = map(pos.xz + nor.xz*dst);
             //float hn = map(mix(vos, pos.xz, .5) + nor.xz*dst);
             //float hn = map(gridID(pos.xz + nor.xz*dst)*s);
             occ -= (dst - max(pos.y + nor.y*dst  - hn, 0.))*k;//*smoothstep(-1., 1., h - hn);
             dst += ds;
             k *= .5;
        }

        occ = clamp(occ, 0., 1.);

        // This is a left over line from IQ's cylinder traversal example that I
        // forgot to take out until after the coloring was done, so it's here to stay. :)
        // If you were to attribute some science to it, buildings would be more shadowy
        // at ground level... Yeah, I'm not convinced either. :D
        occ *= pow(clamp((pos.y + .01)/(h + .01), 0., 1.), 2.);
        // Manipulating for whatever shade we're after. 
        occ = mix(occ, occ*occ, .5)*.8 + .2;

        // Lighting.


        // Diffuse lighting term.
        float dif = max(dot(nor, ld), 0.);

        // Shadows.
        //
        // Old fashioned hard shadows. Not as nice as soft ones, but still appreciated. :) 
        // Actually, if you were path tracing, then soft shadows would be the result anyway.
        // You could also blur these on a separate buffer then reintegrate.
        float shad = 0.;
        if(dif>0.){ shad = castShadowRay(pos + nor*1e-3, ld); }



        // IQ's rim lighting snippet: For anyone not familiar, he's using 
        // the Fresnel factor for some silhouette lighting.
        float rim = pow(clamp(1. + dot(rd, nor), 0., 1.), 5.);


        // Specular reflection. 
        float spe = pow(clamp(dot(ld, reflect(rd, nor)), 0., 1.), 4.);


        // Putting the above terms together. 
        col = objCol*(dif*shad + .5 + vec3(2, .4, .3)*spe*shad + sky*rim*2.);


        col *= occ;




        #ifdef HEXAGON
        float shape = max(abs(lP.y)*.8660254 + abs(lP.x)*.5, abs(lP.x)) - s.x/2.;
        #else
        vec2 aLP = abs(lP) - s/2.;
        float shape = max(aLP.x, aLP.y);
        #endif

        // Top face edge height.
        float edgeY = pos.y - h;

        // Shape edge.
        float shapeEdge = abs(shape);
        shapeEdge = abs(shapeEdge - edgeY) - .03;


        #ifdef HEXAGON
        // Hexagon vertical edges.
        // Lines eminating from the center to the vertices.
        vec2 p = rot2(3.14159/aNum)*lP; 
        float a = mod(atan(p.x, p.y), 6.2831)/6.2831;
        a = (floor(a*aNum) + .5)/aNum;
        p *= rot2(a*6.2831);
        float edge = abs(p.x) - .02; 
        #else
        vec2 p = lP;
        // Square vertical edges. Much easier. :)
        float edge = -min(abs(p.x) + .04 - s.x/2., abs(p.y) + .04 - s.y/2.);
        #endif

        // Chop out the inside face lines... I'm making this up as
        // I go along. I'll tidy it up later.  :) 
        edge = max(edge, -(shape + .02));


        // Combining the top face edge with the side edges.
        edge = min(edge, shapeEdge);


        // Cheap reflective pass. A full reflective pass would be nicer, but
        // this is the next best thing. Trace out from the hit point along
        // the direction ray. If we hit the scene, add nothing, but if we
        // hit the sky, index into a sky-looking cube map. Not perfect, but
        // any stretch, but it gives a pretty cool reflective pass glow.

        vec3 refl = reflect(rd, nor);
        float resRef = castShadowRay(pos + nor*2e-3, refl);
        //t = resRef.x;

        vec3 refTex = textureLod(iChannel2, refl, 0.).rgb; refTex *= refTex;

        //float rsun = clamp(dot(refl, ld), 0., 1.);
        //vec3 rsky =  mix(vec3(1, .75, .6), vec3(1, .75, .6).xzy, max(rd.y, 0.)*.5);
        //rsky = (rsky + .3*pow(rsun, 4.));
        vec3 spec = resRef<.5? vec3(0) : refTex*4. ;

        float fr = mix(.03, .25, pow(max(0., 1. + dot(rd, nor)), 3.));

        col = mix(col, spec, fr);

        // Occlusion debug.
        //col = vec3(occ);



        // Applying edges at the end.
        float sf = 3./450.*(1.35 + t*t*.005);
        col = mix(col, col*1.8, (1. - smoothstep(0., sf, edge - .05))); 
        col = mix(col, col*.1, (1. - smoothstep(0., sf, edge))); 



        // Fogging out to the horizon..
        col = mix( col, sky, smoothstep(0., 1., t*t/140./140.));
        //col = mix(sky, col, exp(-t*t/120./120.)); // Alternative.

    }

    // Another one of IQ's touches that I like. Running a small portion of sunlight
    // over the whole scene for a little extra scattering.
    col += pow(sun, 8.)*.08;

    // Subtle vignette.
    uv = fragCoord/iResolution.xy;
    col = clamp(col, 0., 1.)*pow(16.*uv.x*uv.y*(1. - uv.x)*(1. - uv.y) , 1./32.);




    // This is IQ's temporal reprojection code: It's well written and
    // it makes sense. I wrote some 2D reprojection code and was not
    // looking forward to writing the 3D version, and then this 
    // suddenly appeared on Shadertoy. If you're interested in rigid 
    // realtime path traced scenes with slowly moving cameras, this is 
    // much appreciated. :)
    //
    #ifdef REPROJECTION
    //-----------------------------------------------
	// Reproject to previous frame and pull history.
    //-----------------------------------------------

    float kFocLen = 1./FOV;
    vec3 pos = resPos;
    ivec2 q = ivec2(fragCoord);
    col = clamp(col, 0., 1.);

    // fetch previous camera matrix from the bottom left three pixels
    mat3x4 oldCam = mat3x4(texelFetch(iChannel3, ivec2(0, 0), 0),
                           texelFetch(iChannel3, ivec2(1, 0), 0),
                           texelFetch(iChannel3, ivec2(2, 0), 0));
    // World space point.
    vec4 wpos = vec4(pos, 1.);
    // Convert to camera space (note inverse multiply).
    vec3 cpos = wpos*oldCam;
    // Convert to NDC space (project).
    vec2 npos = (kFocLen*2.)*cpos.xy/cpos.z;//*iRes/iResolution.y;
    // Convert to screen space.
    vec2 spos = .5 + .5*npos*vec2(iResolution.y/iResolution.x, 1);
	// Convert to raster space.
    vec2 rpos = spos*iResolution.xy;

    // Read color+depth from this point's previous screen location.
    vec4 ocolt = textureLod( iChannel3, spos, 0.);
    // If we consider the data contains the history for this point.
    if(iFrame>0 && resT<FAR && (rpos.y>1.5 ||rpos.x>3.5)){

        // Blend with history (it's an IIR low pas filter really).
        col = mix( ocolt.xyz, col, 1./4.);
    }

    // Color and depth.
    fragColor = vec4(col, resT);

    // Output.
	if(q.y == 0 && q.x<3){

    	// Camera matrix in lower left three pixels, for next frame.
        if(q.x == 0) fragColor = vec4(mCam[0], -dot(mCam[0], ro));
        else if(q.x == 1) fragColor = vec4( mCam[1], -dot(mCam[1], ro));
        else fragColor = vec4( mCam[2], -dot(mCam[2], ro));
    } 
    #else
    // Mix the previous frames in with no camera reprojection.
    // It's OK, but full temporal blur will be experienced.
